<head ><name  n='ancient scholarship' type='ancientGenre'>Ancient Scholarship</name></head>
<p >Just as modern scholars read and comment on the work of ancient historians, orators, and poets, so too did ancient scholars. Scholars like <name  type='ancientAuthor'>Dionysius</name> of <placeName  key='Halicarnassus'>Halicarnassus</placeName>, <name  type='ancientAuthor'>Libanius</name>, or <name  type='ancientAuthor'>Didymus</name> wrote commentaries on ancient authors and works. These ancient scholars addressed issues of style (<quote >What are the defining characteristics of <name  type='ancientAuthor'>Demosthenes</name>’ rhetorical style?</quote>) authorship (<quote >Did <name  type='ancientAuthor'>Demosthenes</name> actually write the speech <title >On <placeName  key='Halonnesus'>Halonnesus</placeName>?</title>,</quote> see <bibl  n='urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0014.tlg007' type='cts-urn'>Dem. 7</bibl>), or details of content (<quote >When <name  type='ancientAuthor'>Homer</name> mentions a door-lock, what kind of door-lock is he describing?</quote>). While these ancient scholars were just as likely to make mistakes as modern scholars, they did have access to many works that have not survived to the present day. A significant work in this genre is the <rs  n='http://www.stoa.org/sol/' type='uri'><name  type='ancientAuthor'>Suda</name></rs>, a historical encyclopedia from the <date  from='0900' to='0999'>10th century CE</date>, that provides many quotations from lost authors, discussions of word-usage, and historical anecdotes.</p>
<byline >Christopher Blackwell</byline>
